    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-01T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-01T16:00:00-05:00" n="361"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-01T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 1, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1080. Your 1514, April 29. The release of the tripartite statement was held up at
                    the last minute at the request of the British Foreign Office. Since last
                        Thursday<note n="56" xml:id="d361fn56">April 27.</note> nothing whatever has
                    been heard from London on the matter and the British Embassy here states that it
                    has received no reply to its telegram asking for the reasons for the
                    postponement and for a proposal for a new release date.</p>
                <p>The Department has requested the Embassy at London<note n="57" xml:id="d361fn57"
                        >In telegram 3487, May 1, 5 p.m., not printed.</note> urgently to take up
                    the matter with the Foreign Office and to inform you of its reply. We think that
                    the statement should be used now if it is to be effective, particularly in view
                    of Stalin’s treatment of the same matter in his order of the day.<note n="58"
                        xml:id="d361fn58">See telegram 1538, May 1, from Moscow, <ref
                            target="frus1944v04#pg_864">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p.
                            864</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
